defaultAlthough we must always express caution when making direct comparisons between countries which have d
defaultifferent cultures and variables 
defaultthere is a great deal of evidence from countries such as 
defaultCroatia, 
defaultNorway
default and Belgium 
defaultthat show 
defaultincreases in donation rates following 
default a move to an opt-out 
defaultsystem
default together with
default investment in infrastructure and raising public awareness
default of organ donation.
default 
defaultFor example in Norway
default,
default 
defaultwhere an
default opt-out system has operated since 1973
default,
default 
defaultthere 
defaulthas
default 
defaultbeen
default significant investment in 
defaultthe
default infrastructure – with Europe’s largest single transplant centre based in Oslo and five transplant co-ordinators to aid retrieval across the country. Norway’s rate of donation in 2011 was 24.5 
defaultper million population (
defaultpmp
default)
default,
default which was well above the European average.
default 
defaultIn Belgium the rate of organ donation increased from 19 to 41 
defaultpmp
default three years after the introduction of opt-out legislation. 
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Croatian model provides a clear example that a move to opt-out alone would not provide the much needed organ increase. 
defaultIn 2000,
default 
defaultCroatia
default 
defaulthad one of the lowest donor rates 
defaultpmp
default in Europe at just 2.7 
defaultpmp
default despite moving to an opt
default-
defaultout system 12 years previously. Yet after a period of significant 
defaultinvestment
default by 2011 Croatia had one of the highest rates of donation in Europe of 33.6 
defaultpmp
default.
default 
default To achieve this, there was heavy investment in 
defaultdeveloping
default an ‘in-house’ 
defaulttransplant co-ordinator network in all hospitals which improved donor detection and management of potential donors. This approach also helped to reduce family refusal rate to 
default20 per cent, which is less than half of the UK’s current refusal rate.
default A 24 hour helpline was set up at the Ministry of Health to support transplant co-ordinators 
defaultdeliver
default 
defaulta speedy and efficient donor-transplant process. 
defaultFurthermore there has 
defaultbeen significant investment in public awareness campaigns organ
defaultised by the Ministry of Health 
defaultand non-governmental organisations such as the Croatian Donor Network. There has also been continuous education and organ donor card promotion. 
